\introduction %% \introduction[modified heading if necessary]
Agriculture occupies around X\% of the Earth's terrestrial surface and
consumes(?) around 85\% of its freshwater resources \citep{}. As a
result of extensive land use change and agricultural intensification
to meet the world's growing food demand, agriculture has substantially
altered the global hydrological and ecological cycle
\citep{gordon_managing_2010}. At the same time, agriculture supports
the livelihoods of almost X\% of the global population. Crop
simulation models are widely used by scientists, policy-makers and
practitioners to understand the response of crop yield to biophysical
variables including soil fertility, water availability and atmospheric
composition \citep{}. Historically, these models have been developed
for point-scale simulations of crop processes, with the prinicpal aim
to optimise management strategies to maximize crop yield \citep{}.
However, given the regional importance of agriculture as a land
use... there has been Gridded crop models have been developed... to
enable the consistent evaluation of crop productivity in response to
environmental change and hence to identify vulnerabilities in
agricultural systems at regional and global levels
\citep{elliott_global_2015}. The Global Gridded Crop Model
Intercomparison (GGCMI) \citep{elliott_global_2015} initiative, which
contributes to the broader Agricultural Model Intercomparison and
Improvement Project (AgMIP), has enabled the comparison of crop models
within a consistent framework.\\

The FAO AquaCrop model focuses on water productivity. It supports
multiple crop sequences and rotations. In it's standard interface, the
model is designed to simulate crop growth and associated variables at
one point in space. A key limitation of the original implementation of
AquaCrop, however, is that is was distributed as a binary executable
\citep{}, which means that results generated... are not reproducible
and... makes it extremely difficult for the community to extend and
adapt the model for their own purposes \citep{}. Addressing this
shortcoming, \citet{foster_aquacrop-os_2017} released a version of the
model, programmed in Matlab/Octave, as open source software. Since the
model is relatively parsimonious compared to some crops models... it
is well suited to gridded applications. In addition to the standard
interface, the model has been included in a plug-in for ArcGIS,
enabling the model to be run over a spatial grid \citep{}. In effect,
each grid cell contains a single AquaCrop simulation... input data and
parameters can be supplied as a raster image \citep{}. While
AquaCrop-OS can be adapted to model crop production over multiple
points during the same model run, it is structured to explicitly
handle space in a way that is consistent with conventions adopted in
Earth system science, particularly with respect to their handling of
input and output data.\\

According to \citep{rosenzweig_assessing_2014}, the various models
participating in the GGCMI initiative may be divided into three types
according to their structure, representation of processes and original
purpose. Site-based models, including EPIC, GEPIC and pDSSAT, were
originally developed to simulate crop growth at the field scale
\citep{}, and are frequently ``calibrated and validated with data from
agronomic field experiments'' \citep{rosenzweig_assessing_2014}. These
models have been wrapped in a spatial framework to facilitate their
application over a grid... \citep{}. The interfaces of these models
have been adapted... Several of these models participate in the Global
Gridded Crop Model Intercomparison project, an initiative under the
AgMIP umbrella which aims
to... \citep{elliott_global_2015,mueller_global_2017}. Additionally,
they may be used in coupled Earth system frameworks to improve the
representation of water and energy fluxes from the land surface
\citep{tsarouchi_???_2014}.

% Notes from Rosenzweig et al. (2014)
The need to understand climate change impacts on crop productivity has
given rise to gridded crops models \citep{rosenzweig_assessing_2014}.

Previously, a lack of consistency between protocols used to run
gridded crop models made it difficult to quantify the uncertainty
associated with the predicted climate change impacts and made it
difficult to devise appropriate adaptation strategies
\citep{white_methodologies_2011,roetter_crop-climate_2011}. The GGCMI
was initiated to resolve these shortcomings by providing a consistent
simulation protocol for gridded crop models, including the provision
of consistent forcing datasets as well as a set of common objectives
to address in experiments \citep{rosenzweig_assessing_2014}. All
models are forced with a common set of bias-corrected climate data
from the CMIP5 archive \citep{}. Minimally, the GGCMI aims to identify
and examine the spatio-temporal patterns in the response of crop
productivity to changes in climate and atmospheric composition.

Environmental Policy Integrated Model (EPIC); GIS-based Environmental
Policy Integrated Model (GEPIC). Site-based models were developed to
perform crop simulations at the field scale
\citep{rosenzweig_assessing_2014}. They are frequently calibrated and
validated against field data, and used to advance process
understanding and optimise management strategies
\citep{mueller_global_2017}. Several site-based models have been
adapted to run simulations over a spatial grid (e.g. DSSAT). The main
purpose of agro-ecosystem models is to geochemical cycles and the
surface energy and water balance \citep{rosenzweig_assessing_2014}. In
models such LPJmL and LPJ-GUESS, crop development was originally
included to improve the representation of these processes
\citep{schaphoff_lpjml4_2018}.

% Notes from Mueller et al. (2017)
In recent decades it has become apparent that agricultural productivity is influenced by climate change \citep{mueller_global_2017}. Population growth and socioeconomic development, including processes such as urbanisation, puts additional pressure on global food security. Meanwhile agricultural systems place increasing pressure on important ecosystem services including the provision of freshwater resources, biodiversity and the ``terrestrial carbon sink'' \citep{lequere_???_2015}, with an emerging consensus that a collective dietary shift which dramatically reduces global meat consumption is necessary to limit the effects of climate change \citep{}. Meanwhile agricultural systems have a large impact on catchment-scale processes. To address the scientific and and policy questions associated with these phenomena, gridded crop models have been developed and applied at a variety of spatial scales. A prominent initiative is the Global Gridded Crop Model Intercomparison (GGCMI).\\

Global and regional crop models cannot be calibrated and validated
against field observations \citep{mueller_global_2017}. Models are
typically sensitive to to soil properties; reliable soil information,
even at the local scale, is notoriously difficult to find \citep{}.

In this paper we describe an implementation of AquaCrop written in the Python programming language which is open source and explicitly represents space. The underlying science code is cloned from the Matlab/Octave implementation, and the implementation may still be used as a site-based model. However, the model interface contains several innovations which are likely to broaden the appeal of AquaCrop to members of the Earth system modelling community. We describe the concept and implementation of these features in more detail in the following section, before introducing an example application of the model to the Indo-Gangetic Plain in northern India. \\

\section{The FAO AquaCrop model}
The AquaCrop model is comprehensively described in the accompanying
publications \citep{} and model manual \citep{}. AquaCrop-OS is
described in \citep{foster_aquacrop-os_2017}. For completeness, we
provide an overview of the main concepts here. AquaCrop improves and
updates the FAO Irrigation Drainage Paper 33 \citep{}, which
``represents crop yield response to water as a linear, crop-specific
function of the ratio of actual to potential evapotranspiration over a
growing season''.

