\subsection{Input and output}
We use Unidata's netCDF library for input parameters, meteorological
forcing data and model outputs. NetCDF ``is a software library that
reads and writes self-describing array-oriented scientific data with
its metadata. It has been widely adopted among the geoscientific
modeling community and provides a convenient self-describing
machine-independent data format.''. The Python interface to the netCDF
library is used. The model includes methods to regrid input data so
that is consistent with the extent and resolution of the model
domain. One side-effect of this feature is to render pre-processing of
global input data unnecessary, hence saving time and minimising
opportunity for user-error \citep{}. Where possible, output netCDF
files are consistent with the netCDF Climate and Forecast (CF)
metadata conventions version 1.6 \citep{eaton2009}. Variables to be
written to file are specified in the configuration file. In addition,
summary values can be output at monthly or annual intervals. Each
output variable is written to a separate netCDF file.

\subsection{Spatio-temporal framework}
Description of the PCRaster framework, and NumPy library. Input/output
data in netCDF format. Describe how sub-grid heterogeneity is
handled. Capacity for model coupling. Object-oriented, with each class
implementing, as a minimum, ``initial'' and ``dynamic'' methods. The
former is used to initialize the data structures, while the latter is
used to update the model state variables during each time step. The
PCRaster framework essentially handles model timestepping. Whereas the
framework has in the past been used for map algebra in Python, we
instead prefer to use the NumPy \citep{} library for this, because of
its support for multi-dimensional arrays, powerful function
library... and inbuilt test support \citep{}. At runtime, the spatial
dimensions of NumPy arrays containing model data are flattened in
order to avoid processing grid cells which are not part of the model
domain.

\subsection{Farm-level modelling}
Besides the explicit representation of space, AquaCrop-Py additionally allows the model to be further disaggregated into farm units. The aim here is to facilitate agent-based models - ``Socialize the pixel'' - within the spatial framework. \\

Talk about inclusion of an irrigation water supply module, which allows users to supply daily data about irrigation water availability. The purpose here is to allow model users to couple the model with a water supply module. \\

