\section{Application}
We demonstrate the new interface through an application to the
Indo-Gangetic Plain in northern India. In the first part of the
experiment, we follow the GGCMI Phase 1 simulation protocol to
simulate the productivity of GGCMI Priority 1 crops, consisting of
wheat, maize, soy and rice, over the historical period
1980--2010. Subsequently, we combine the model with maps of irrigated
and rainfed area in order to estimate the irrigative water demand of
rice-wheat systems across the study area.

\subsection{Input data}
Input data is consistent with the GGCMI Phase 1 simulation protocol
\citep{elliott_global_2015}. We use WATCH-Forcing-Data-ERA-Interim
(WFDEI) data \citep{}. Evapotranspiration was calculated using the
meteorological forcing data. Soil properties from the ISRIC SoilGrids
database \citep{}. Crop parameter values were obtained from various
sources. First, we identified crop parameter values... default
AquaCrop parameters. Of those remaining, we performed a literature
search... Implement GGCMI ``harmonized'' management practice data with
respect to planting date, growing season length [and fertilizer
inputs] \citep{elliott_global_2015,mueller_global_2017}. Soil
properties were derived from the ISRIC SoilGrids product
\citep{}. Whilst AquaCrop uses a relatively small number of parameters
compared to other process-based crop models \citep{}, each modelled
crop still requires approximately n parameters. Since our purpose here
is to demonstrate the capabilities of the model interface, rather than
to test the underlying model, we have used default parameter values
available from X \citep{}.

